xxl.core.functions
Class ArrayFactory<T>

java.lang.Object
  xxl.core.functions.AbstractFunction<java.lang.Object,T[]>
      xxl.core.functions.ArrayFactory<T>
Type Parameters:
T - the component type of the array to be returned.
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.io.Serializable, Function<java.lang.Object,T[]>
public class ArrayFactory<T>
extends AbstractFunction<java.lang.Object,T[]>

This class provides a factory method for typed arrays. The ArrayFactory creates an array and fills it with objects. An iterator of arguments can be passed to the invoke method of this class to create the objects which are stored in the array.

Method Detail

invoke

public T[] invoke(java.util.List<? extends java.lang.Object> arguments)
Returns the result of the ArrayFactory as a typed array. This method calls the invoke method of the newArray function which returns an array of typed objects. After this, the invoke method of the newObject function is called, so many times as the length of the array. As parameter to the function an element of the iterator is given that is specified as second argument.

Specified by:
invoke in interface Function<java.lang.Object,T[]>
Overrides:
invoke in class AbstractFunction<java.lang.Object,T[]>
Parameters:
arguments - the arguments to this function. The first arguments must be an object used as argument to the newArray function. The second argument must be an iterator holding the arguments to the newObject function.
Returns:
the initialized array.

invoke

public T[] invoke(java.lang.Object argument)
Returns the result of the ArrayFactory as a typed array. This method calls the invoke method of the newArray function using the given argument which returns an array of typed objects. After this, the invoke method of the newObject function is called without any arguments, so many times as the length of the array.

Specified by:

invoke

public T[] invoke()
Returns the result of the ArrayFactory as a typed array. This method calls the invoke method of the newArray function using the argument null which returns an array of typed objects. After this, the invoke method of the newObject function is called without any arguments, so many times as the length of the array.
